{"name": "Is The World Getting Better?", "id": 206, "content": "<p>The words &quot;<strong><em>better</em></strong>&quot; and &quot;<strong><em>worse</em></strong>&quot; are very broad terms.</p>\n\n<p>Let&#39;s see situations from different perspectives:</p>\n\n<p><u><strong>Individual Aspect</strong></u>: What is the condition of the world on an individual level? A person needs these things in general:-</p>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li><strong>Food</strong> - There are people dying from overeating (obesity) and undereating (starvation).</li>\n\t<li><strong>Health</strong><br />\n\t- Physical - There are people consuming excessive protein, steroids, and then there are people suffering from malnutrition.<br />\n\t- Mental - There are people living a happy life, and there are people suffering from depression (many a time leading to suicides)</li>\n\t<li><strong>House, Shelter -</strong>&nbsp;there are people with excessive space, land, multiple houses, and then there are homeless people.</li>\n\t<li><strong>Education</strong> -&nbsp;<br />\n\t&nbsp;There is a lot of things to consider in terms of education. How many are still not getting the basic education? Is the format of educational system correct as it is? How much are we investing in &quot;real&quot; education along with vocational training? But most importantly &quot;<em>How many children are still not going to schools?</em>&quot;</li>\n\t<li><strong>Employment</strong> -<br />\n\tAre people getting jobs? Are people satisfied with their jobs?</li>\n\t<li><strong>Social Inclusion</strong> -&nbsp;<br />\n\tWe now have media through which we can communicate with people who are thousands of miles away. But is this communication effective in making <em>connections</em>?</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><strong><u>Planet Earth Aspect</u>:</strong>&nbsp;What about the <em>home</em> of every single person?</p>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li><strong>Environment/Climate</strong>: There are many concerns when it comes to Climate Change.<br />\n\t&nbsp; &nbsp; Global Warming</li>\n\t<li><strong>Natural Resources</strong>:&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\n\t&nbsp; &nbsp; Exhaustion of resources</li>\n\t<li><strong>Overpopulation</strong></li>\n\t<li><strong>Pollution</strong><br />\n\t<strong>&nbsp; </strong>- Water Pollution, Ocean Acidification<br />\n\t&nbsp; - Air Pollution, Acid Rain<br />\n\t&nbsp; - Waste Disposal</li>\n\t<li><strong>Loss Biodiversity, Habitat</strong></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><strong><u>Society Aspect</u>:</strong>&nbsp;Humans cannot survive and thrive on their own, that&#39;s why they form groups. &quot;Society&quot; is a general group encompassing many individuals.</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li><strong>Social Co-ordination</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">Discriminations:<br />\n\t&nbsp;- Men/Women, other sex discrimination<br />\n\t&nbsp;-&nbsp;Racial discrimination<br />\n\t&nbsp;-&nbsp;Occupational discrimination, economic discrimination<br />\n\t&nbsp;-&nbsp;Caste discrimination<br />\n\t&nbsp;-&nbsp;Religious discrimination<br />\n\t&nbsp;-&nbsp;Ideological discrimination</li>\n\t<li style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">Inequality</li>\n\t<li style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">Crime</li>\n\t<li style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">Terrorism</li>\n\t<li style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">Internal (Intra-group) Conflicts, Wars</li>\n\t<li style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">Inter-group conflicts and wars (conflicts b/w countries, states, and other forms of groups etc)</li>\n</ol>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li><strong>Political Stability</strong></li>\n\t<li><strong>Market (Economic) Stability</strong>: Economy is a crucial part of human civilization as far as we know it.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Food and Nourishment</h2>\n\n<p><strong>Undernourishment in the whole world&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong></p>\n\n<div style=\"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;\"><span style=\"font-size:28px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Trebuchet MS,Helvetica,sans-serif;\">13.1%</span></span>&nbsp; in 2007&rarr;&nbsp; <span style=\"color:#2ecc71;\"><span style=\"font-family:Trebuchet MS,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:26px;\">10.9%</span></span></span> in 2017&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\n\n<p><strong>&quot;Severe&quot; food insecurity in the whole world</strong></p>\n\n<div style=\"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;\"><span style=\"font-size:26px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Trebuchet MS,Helvetica,sans-serif;\">8.9%</span></span> in 2016&nbsp;&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp; <span style=\"font-size:26px;\">10.2%</span> in 2017</div>\n\n<p><br />\n<strong>Which places are suffering the most?</strong></p>\n\n<p>If we go by the number of people suffering, this is the list of top 20 countries (in decreasing order) :-</p>\n\n<div style=\"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;\">India &rarr;&nbsp;China&nbsp;&rarr; Pakistan&nbsp;&rarr; Bangladesh&nbsp;&rarr; Ethiopia&nbsp;&rarr; Nigeria&nbsp;&rarr; Indonesia&nbsp;&rarr; Tanzania&nbsp;&rarr; Uganda&nbsp;&rarr; Philippines&nbsp;&rarr; Kenya&nbsp;&rarr; Korea&nbsp;&rarr; Madagascar&nbsp;&rarr; Afghanistan&nbsp;&rarr; Iraq&nbsp;&rarr; Vietnam&nbsp;&rarr; Sudan&nbsp;&rarr; Yemen&nbsp;&rarr; Mozambique&nbsp;&rarr; Zimbabwe</div>\n\n<p>I am not writing the list by percentage (its available in the book <a href=\"http://www.fao.org/publications/card/en/c/CA1796EN\" target=\"_blank\">2018 UN FAO Statistical Pocket Book</a>).&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>Why are so many people suffering from Food Insecurity?</strong></p>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li>Food Availability, Supply - depending on transportation, climate, political conflicts.</li>\n\t<li>Food Access - depending on personal income, food prices, physical access.</li>\n\t<li>Stability - depends on supply shortfall, price swings, conflicts, climate change, etc. Over the last ten years, things have not been stable.</li>\n\t<li>Food Utilization - depends on Nutrients in food, clean environment, access to healthcare, intra-household distribution of food.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>Source:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.fao.org/publications/card/en/c/CA1796EN\" target=\"_blank\">2018 UN FAO Statistical Pocket Book</a></p>\n\n<p>Meanwhile, the number of people suffering from obesity has increased: Obesity depends on many factors: Excessive consumption of food (calories), Sedentary (inactive) lifestyle, lack of sleep, medications, genes and internal body factors.</p>\n\n<div style=\"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;\">\n<ul>\n\t<li>Worldwide obesity has nearly tripled since 1975.</li>\n\t<li>In 2016, more than 1.9 billion (39%) adults, 18 years and older, were overweight. Of these over 650 million (13%) were obese.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<p>Source:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/obesity-and-overweight\" target=\"_blank\">WHO Report</a></p>\n\n<h2>Health</h2>\n\n<p>Source: <a href=\"http://www.who.int/features/factfiles/global_burden/en/\" target=\"_blank\">WHO Facts</a></p>\n\n<div style=\"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;\">Global Average Life Expectancy has increased by 5 years b/w 2000 and 2015, the fastest increase since the 1960s. In simple words, <em>people are more likely to be alive for 5 more years now than they were in 2000</em>.</div>\n\n<p>16000 children under 5 died <strong>every day,&nbsp;</strong>and almost all of them could be saved with access to exclusive breastfeeding, medication, health facility, sanitation.</p>\n\n<p>Stillborn babies (2.6 million in 2015) are not registered in records, and hence countries (organizations) do not get to know the actual situation of children dying, why are they dying etc.</p>\n\n<p>5 million injuries caused death in 2015, 27% of these due to road traffic injuries.</p>\n\n<div style=\"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;\">In 2015:&nbsp; &nbsp;<span style=\"font-family:Trebuchet MS,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">18.3</span></span>&nbsp;(28.5 in low-income countries) per 100,000 people died in <strong><em>traffic injuries</em></strong>&nbsp; &amp; <span style=\"font-family:Trebuchet MS,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">10.7</span>&nbsp;(14.5 in high-income countries)&nbsp;</span>per 100,000 due to <strong><em>suicide</em></strong>. However, 79% of suicides still in low-income and medium-income countries (<a href=\"http://www.who.int/mental_health/prevention/suicide/suicideprevent/en/\" target=\"_blank\">Source</a>).<br />\n<br />\nClose to 800 000 people die due to suicide every year, which is <span style=\"font-size:20px;\">one</span> person every <span style=\"font-size:20px;\">40</span> seconds. Suicide is a global phenomenon and occurs throughout the lifespan.&nbsp;</div>\n\n<p>Mental health problems are more occurrent in the high-income countries than the low-income countries.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Is the problem of suicide increasing?&nbsp;</strong></p>\n\n<p>- It seems so. Read these: <a href=\"https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-44416727\" target=\"_blank\">BBC article</a>, <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.in/The-CDC-just-released-staggering-data-on-the-rise-in-suicides-across-the-US-It-shows-the-growing-severity-of-the-issue-/articleshow/64500894.cms\" target=\"_blank\">Business Insider article</a>.</p>\n\n<div style=\"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;\">\n<ul>\n\t<li>Depression is a common mental disorder. Globally, more than 300 million people of all ages suffer from depression. (Source: <a href=\"http://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/depression\" target=\"_blank\">WHO Facts</a>)</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<p>Epidemics: Source <a href=\"http://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/managing-epidemics/en/\" target=\"_blank\">WHO</a>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Epidemic events&nbsp;globally, 2011 &ndash; 2017: A total of 1,307 epidemic events</p>\n\n<div style=\"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;\">The number of epidemic events has not gone below much between 2011 and 2017. In 2011 the count was 179, in 2017 it was 189+.</div>\n\n<p>New lifestyles spread diseases further. Risk communication is now easier due to technologies, but due to information pollution, it is also difficult.</p>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:#4e5f70;\"><strong>List of Deadly Diseases</strong></span>:</p>\n\n<div style=\"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;\">Yellow fever, Chikungunya, Viral haemorrhagic fever, Ebola virus disease, Marburg virus disease, Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever, Rift Valley fever, Cholera, Typhoid fever, Shigellosis, Plague, Lassa fever, West Nile fever, Zika virus disease, Meningitis, MERS-CoV, Influenza A, Monkeypox, Nodding syndrome, Nipah virus infection</div>\n\n<p>This book describes details of these epidemic diseases. WHO Book <a href=\"http://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/managing-epidemics-interactive.pdf?ua=1\" target=\"_blank\">Managing Epidemics</a>.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Has there been an improvement in the health sector?</strong></p>\n\n<p>By and large, certainly there has been an improvement. New kinds of diseases will keep coming. But we have significantly reduced the damage done by many diseases. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eradication_of_infectious_diseases\" target=\"_blank\">List of diseases either </a><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eradication_of_infectious_diseases\" target=\"_blank\">eradicated</a><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eradication_of_infectious_diseases\" target=\"_blank\">&nbsp;or on their way to eradication</a>.</p>\n\n<h2>Housing</h2>\n\n<p>870 million people are living in inadequate housing arrangements. Source: <a href=\"https://www.ohchr.org/EN/Issues/Housing/Pages/AnnualReports.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">UN General Assembly statement</a>. Inadequate settlements include Slums (on the outskirt of cities, and also within cities), Refugee camps, other shelters with insufficient access to required resources like food, sanitation, water etc.</p>\n\n<h2>Education<br 