 being treated or reused (UNESCO, 2017).</li>\n\t<li>Around two-thirds of the world&rsquo;s transboundary rivers do not have a cooperative management framework. (SIWI)</li>\n\t<li>Agriculture accounts for 70% of global water withdrawal. (FAO)</li>\n\t<li>Roughly 75% of all industrial water withdrawals are used for energy production.&nbsp;(UNESCO, 2014)</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<p>See more at <a href=\"http://www.un.org/en/sections/issues-depth/water/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">UN Issues Depth Water</a>.</p>\n\n<h2>Discriminations</h2>\n\n<p>It&#39;s hard to quantify the discriminations because most of the times&nbsp;discrimination does not occur in an organized way but they are entangled in daily life. We can have an estimate of the situation on discrimination by looking at how many laws are there to prevent discriminations, what incidents took place, how many organizations are there working against discriminations etc.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2>Male-Female Discriminations&nbsp;</h2>\n\n<p><strong>How were women treated?</strong></p>\n\n<p>From a global perspective, it can be said that women&nbsp;were not treated in a way they should have been. The main problems concerning male-female discrimination are:&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Lack of Freedom, Violence against them, Lack of involvement in social frameworks (e.g. Parliament, Government, Business etc), Lack of Education, Treatment as Property or Thing (including Trafficking, Prostitution, Slavery (intra-household) etc).</p>\n\n<p><strong>How are they treated now?</strong></p>\n\n<p>In a better way. There has been an improvement with regards to each of the problems listed above. But still, the problem persists on each level.</p>\n\n<p>Visit&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.unwomen.org/en/what-we-do/ending-violence-against-women/facts-and-figures\" target=\"_blank\">UN Women Violence Facts</a>&nbsp;for facts and figures regarding this discrimination.</p>\n\n<h2>Racial Discriminations</h2>\n\n<p>Read <a href=\"https://www.telesurenglish.net/analysis/The-Top-12-Most-Racist-Countries-in-the-World-20150320-0019.html\">TelesureEnglish - Most Racist Countries</a></p>\n\n<p>Top 12 List: USA &rarr; Saudi Arabia &rarr; UK &rarr; Japan &rarr; Germany &rarr; Israel &rarr; South Africa &rarr; Australia &rarr; Rwanda &rarr; Russia &rarr; Pakistan &rarr; India</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.globalissues.org/article/165/racism\">Global Issues - Racism</a></p>\n\n<p>The most common instances of Racism in history is seen in American Slavery Culture, S. Africa&#39;s Apartheid, Germany&#39;s Rise Of Nazism and the result of it.</p>\n\n<p><strong>How to fathom world situation on this topic?</strong></p>\n\n<p>See how many cases occur? How political parties are playing this and how are they performing?</p>\n\n<p>Nowadays racial discrimination is kind of mixed with <em>immigrant discrimination</em>. Due to Globalization, a lot of people are migrating from one place to other, and the natives are acting against it. This kind of discrimination is being observed throughout the world: US, UK, Germany, Japan, Australia, Spain etc.</p>\n\n<div style=\"background:#eeeeee;border:1px solid #cccccc;padding:5px 10px;\">In 2008, a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.uws.edu.au/social_sciences/soss/research/challenging_racism\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"External Link: 'Challenging Racism: The Anti-Racism Research Project', University of Western Sydney\">study</a>&nbsp;found that Australians, in general, are welcoming of diversity but some&nbsp;<a href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/7641158.stm\" title=\"External Link: 'Australian racism \u201cstill serious\u201d', BBC, September 29, 2008\">1 in 10 Australians still hold racist views</a>&nbsp;&mdash; a ratio likely to be less than in some European countries, but still high the lead researcher noted. Muslims were most feared or loathed for&nbsp;<q>not belonging</q>, and followed by indigenous Australians and Africans.</div>\n\n<h2><br />\nReligious Discriminations</h2>\n\n<p><strong